vina and the [[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]]]\n* [http://hrw.org/reports/2004/ij/icty/2.htm Summary of the ICTY verdicts related to the conflict between Bosnia and Herzegovina and Croatia]\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.familylinks.icrc.org/mis_bos.nsf/bottin |title=List of people missing from the war |access-date=16 June 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090403021929/http://www.familylinks.icrc.org/mis_bos.nsf/bottin |archive-date=3 April 2009 |url-status=bot: unknown }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060617152310/http://www.ess.uwe.ac.uk/comexpert/ANX/VIII-01.htm UN report on prison camps during the war]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070312022449/http://www.unhchr.ch/tbs/doc.nsf/0/333378630589b6d680256674005bc280?Opendocument Open UN document on Serb atrocities towards non-Serbs]\n* Roy, Pinaki. \"''Bosnian War Requiems'': Snippets of the Balkan Commemorations\". ''The Atlantic Critical Review Quarterly''. 10(4), October\u2013December 2011. pp.&nbsp;95\u2013115. {{ISBN|978-81-269-1675-7}}, ISSN 0972-6373.\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.balkanpeace.org/wcs/wct/wcts/index.shtml |title=Serbian War Crime Testimonies |accessdate=2006-06-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20011201013232/http://www.balkanpeace.org/wcs/wct/wcts/index.shtml |archivedate=1 December 2001 |df=dmy }} {{Copyvio link}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090302141103/http://www.throughmyeyes.org.uk/server/show/nav.23333 Through My Eyes Website] Imperial War Museum \u2013 Online Exhibition (Including images, video and interviews with refugees from the war in Bosnia)\n*[http://omniatlas.com/maps/europe/19920622/ Map of Europe showing the Bosnian War (omniatlas.com)]\n*[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1534774696/ \"Quest For War, and One Green Beret's Subsequent Evolution\" contains insights on postwar activities by \"Joint Commissioned Observers\"]\n* {{Citation | url = http://www.heritage.sense-agency.com/ | title = Targeting History and Memory | publisher = SENSE \u2013 Transitional Justice Center}} (dedicated to the study, research, and documentation of the destruction and damage of historic heritage during the Balkan Wars of the 1990s. The website contains judicial documents from the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia (ICTY)).\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Logos|first=Aleksandar|title=Istorija Srba 1, Dopuna 4; Istorija Srba 5|url =https://www.academia.edu/42147440/Istorija_Srba_1_-_Dopuna_4_Istorija_Srba_5_Beograd_ATC_2019.pdf|year=2019|location=Beograd|isbn=978-86-85117-46-6}}\n\n=== Related films ===\n* {{IMDb title|0119873|Warriors}}\n\n{{Bosnian War}}\n{{Yugoslav wars}}\n{{Post-Cold War European conflicts}}\n{{Bosnia and Herzegovina topics}}\n{{Yugoslavia topics}}\n\n[[Category:Bosnian War| ]]\n[[Category:Wars of independence]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Croatia|Bosnia]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Serbia|Bosnia]]\n[[Category:Wars involving NATO|Bosnia]]\n[[Category:1992 in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:1993 in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:1994 in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:1995 in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina\u2013Croatia relations]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1992]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1993]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1994]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1995]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox\u2013Catholic conflicts]]\n", "name_user": "99.189.36.87", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bosnian_War"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)", "text_new": "{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' (CVN-71)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic on board USS ''Theodore Roosevelt''\n| image           = CVN-71-2019-10-01-1.jpg\n| caption         = USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' in October 2019\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n| first_case      = {{ship|USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|2}}\n| arrival_date    = 24 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=24|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 1\n| confirmed_cases = 589<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenney |first1=Caitlin M. |title=Four more USS Theodore Roosevelt sailors hospitalized for the coronavirus|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/navy/four-more-uss-theodore-roosevelt-sailors-hospitalized-for-the-coronavirus-1.626022|accessdate=15 April 2020 |publisher= Stars and Stripes|date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARSCoV-2), the cause of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], was detected on the aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} in March 2020 while she was at sea. Affected crew members were evacuated and the ship was ordered to Guam. The captain, [[Brett Crozier]], wanted most of the crew to be removed from the ship to prevent the spread of the disease, but his superiors balked. After several days Crozier mailed multiple Navy officers begging for the ship to be largely evacuated because the virus could not be contained on board. The letter leaked to the press, and the next day the Navy ordered most of the crew to be taken ashore, but the captain was relieved of command by Acting Secretary of the Navy [[Thomas Modly]]. Modly's order was controversial and his later speech to the crew aboard the ''Roosevelt'', was criticized. Modly resigned a few days later. By mid-April hundreds of crew members including Crozier had tested positive for the virus, and one had died.\n\n==Timeline==\nIn spring 2020, the [[United States Navy]] aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|2}} was on deployment in the Pacific.\n\n===March===\nOn 5 March, the ship made a four-day-long port call at [[Da Nang]], Vietnam. On the last night some sailors stayed at a hotel where two people had tested positive for [[COVID-19]], a coronavirus disease identified as the cause of an outbreak of respiratory illness. Upon learning this, the crew were ordered back to the ship and the sailors who had stayed at the hotel were isolated.<ref name = losses/> The ship departed on 9 March.<ref name=doTimeline>{{cite web |last1=Peniston |first1=Bradley |title=The Battle of USS Theodore Roosevelt: a Timeline |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/04/timeline-battle-uss-theodore-roosevelt/164408/ |website=Defense One |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200411135930/https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/04/timeline-battle-uss-theodore-roosevelt/164408/ |archivedate=11 April 2020 |date=13 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Over the next weeks the ship's medical team monitored the crew for any signs of infection.<ref name = losses/>\n\nOn 22 March, the first sailor tested positive.<ref name=doTimeline/> By 24 March, three sailors aboard had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/24/coronavirus-3-sailors-test-positive-military-readiness-affected/2910165001/ |title=Three sailors from USS Theodore Roosevelt have coronavirus, raising concerns about pandemic's strain on military |work=USA Today |last=Vanden Brook |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Vanden Brook|date=24 March 2020 |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWithin a few days, that number climbed to \"dozens.\" ''Theodore Roosevelt'' was ordered to [[Guam]] and docked on 27 March 2020.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 />\n\nOn 30 March, the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]], sent an [[Classified information in the United States#Unclassified|unclassified email]] to multiple Navy officials asking for help with the coronavirus epidemic on his ship. The email was sent to \"20 or 30\" Naval officers, including members of his staff and others not in his chain of command.<ref name = Cohn>{{Cite news |last=Cohn |first=Lindsay |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/05/this-is-what-was-so-unusual-about-us-navy-making-captain-brett-crozier-step-down/ |title=This is what was so unusual about the U.S. Navy making Captain Brett Crozier step down\u2014Members of the military can face multiple, sometimes competing, loyalties |access-date=6 April 2020 |work=The Washington Post |last2=Friend |first2=Alice |last3=Golby |first3=Jim}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, over 100 sailors tested positive.<ref name=Schogol>{{cite web |last1=Schogol |first1=Jeff |title=Navy captain says COVID-19 is spreading through his aircraft carrier so rapidly that most of the crew needs to get off |url=https://taskandpurpose.com/news/uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus-isolation |website=Task & Purpose |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406231152/https://taskandpurpose.com/news/uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus-isolation |archivedate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The letter was leaked to the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]],'' which published it.<ref name = Gafni>{{cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Exclusive-Captain-of-aircraft-carrier-with-15167883.php |title=Exclusive: Captain of aircraft carrier with growing coronavirus outbreak pleads for help from Navy|last1=Gafni|first1=Matthias |last2=Garofoli|first2=Joe |date=31 March 2020|work=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 1 April, the Navy ordered the aircraft carrier largely evacuated, with a skeleton crew to remain aboard the vessel to maintain the nuclear reactor, the fire-fighting equipment, the ship's galley, and a disinfection crew.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 >{{cite news|last=Peniston|first=Bradley |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/03/us-navy-evacuating-aircraft-carrier-infected-coronavirus/164254/?oref=d-channelriver |title=US Navy Evacuating Aircraft Carrier Infected by Coronavirus|work=Defense One|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]] relieved Crozier of his command.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> According to Modly, Crozier didn't inform his [[Carrier Strike Group 9|superior on the ship]] about sending the letter, and Modly conferred with Crozier's [[chain of command]].<ref name=Gallagher>{{cite web |last1=Gallagher |first1=Sean |title=Aircraft carrier captain lost his command because of \u201cCatch-22\u201d COVID-19 dilemma |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/04/aircraft-carrier-captain-lost-his-command-because-of-catch-22-covid-19-dilemma/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407231021/https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/04/aircraft-carrier-captain-lost-his-command-because-of-catch-22-covid-19-dilemma/ |archivedate=7 April 2020 |language=en-us |date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, the Navy confirmed that 155 sailors had been infected and that 1,500 sailors had been removed from the ship, a lower number than the Navy had projected several days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/sailors-uss-teddy-roosevelt-positive-covid-19-navy |title=155 sailors on USS Theodore Roosevelt test positive for coronavirus, 42 percent of all Navy infections |work=Fox News |last=Ruiz |first=Michael |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Modly traveled to Guam to visit the ship in person.<ref name=\"trip\">{{cite news |title=Blistering Reprimand from Navy Secretary |date=7 April 2020 |author=Helene Cooper |work=[[The New York Times]] |page=A11}}</ref> He made a speech to the crew over the ship's [[public address system]], strongly criticizing Crozier. The transcript and an audio recording of Modly's speech were subsequently leaked to the media.<ref name = Larison/> Later that day, Modly apologized for the comment.<ref name = Casiano>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/acting-navy-secretary-uss-theodore-roosevelt-speech-calls-for-his-firing |title=Trump hints that he may get involved in Navy episode as Modly issues apology|last1=Casiano|first1=Louis |last2=Aaro|first2=David |date=7 April 2020|work=Fox News|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> He resigned from his post the following day.\n\nOn 7 April, the Navy said 61% of ''Theodore Roosevelt''{{'}}s crew had been tested for COVID-19 and 173 members had tested positive, including Captain Crozier. None were hospitalized. Two thousand sailors \u2014 just under half the total crew \u2014 had been moved ashore.<ref name=\"Guardian20200407\">{{cite news |last1=Borger|first1=Julian |last2=|first2=|title=US navy official apologises for calling captain behind coronavirus memo 'naive or stupid' |date=7 April 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/06/navy-coronavirus-ship-theodore-roosevelt-thomas-modly |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, the Navy reported that 416 crew members had tested positive for the virus, and that one quarantined sailor was hospitalized in intensive care after being found unconscious in his quarantine quarters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/uss-theodore-roosevelt-sailor-with-coronavirus-taken-to-icu-2020-4|title=A USS Theodore Roosevelt sailor with coronavirus was taken to the ICU as the number of cases on the aircraft carrier rises|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|date=April 9, 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, it was reported that more than 90% of the crew had been tested for the coronavirus, and 550 crew members had tested positive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/100-new-coronavirus-cases-uss-theodore-roosevelt-550-total-2020-4|title=100 more sailors from the USS Theodore Roosevelt have tested positive for coronavirus, making up 75% of the Navy's total cases worldwide|last=Holmes|first=Aaron|date=11 April 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=McNamara |first1=Audrey |title=Coronavirus cases on USS Theodore Roosevelt spike to 550|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-cases-on-uss-theodore-roosevelt-spike-to-550-2020-04-11/|accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=CBS |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 12 April, 585 crew members had tested positive. <ref name = dies/>\n\nOn 13 April, the hospitalized sailor died.<ref name = dies>politico.com: [https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/13/sailor-uss-roosevelt-dies-coronavirus-183164 ''Sailor from USS Theodore Roosevelt dies of coronavirus'']</ref>\n\n==Crozier's letter==\n[[File:Brett E. Crozier (2).jpg|thumb|Ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]]]]\nWhen the ship arrived in Guam on 26 March the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]], wanted to have most of the crew immediately taken ashore, saying it was impossible to prevent the spread of the virus in the close quarters of the ship. Rear Adm. [[Stuart P. Baker]], who was the commanding officer of [[Carrier Strike Group 9]] and thus Crozier's immediate superior, disagreed, feeling such an action was impractical and too drastic.<ref name = losses>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/coronavirus-roosevelt-carrier-crozier.html?campaign_id=60&emc=edit_na_20200413&instance_id=0&nl=breaking-news&ref=cta&regi_id=16153474&segment_id=24971&user_id=e9848bda5d7546386411f6e2fbdaf95e|title=\u2018There Will Be Losses\u2019: How a Captain\u2019s Plea Exposed a Rift in the Military|date=13 April 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Crozier sent an email to communicate the status of his ship and its crew, saying it was not possible to observe [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]]/Navy<ref>{{cite web |title=Restriction of Movement (ROM) guidance. Navy mitigation measures in response to Novel Coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.public.navy.mil/bupers-npc/reference/messages/Documents/NAVADMINS/NAV2020/NAV20083.txt |publisher=NAVADMIN |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> recommendations for individual quarantine or [[social distancing]] aboard the carrier. Crozier referred to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on Diamond Princess|viral spread on the less crowded cruise ship ''Diamond Princess'']] as an example of [[Basic reproduction number|how quickly a virus can spread]] on a crowded vessel.<ref name = Gafni/><ref name=\"documentcloud\">{{cite web|url=https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/6821571/TR-COVID-19-Assistance-Request.pdf |date=29 March 2020|title=Request for assistance in response to COVID-19 pandemic |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Voltaire>{{cite web |title=Request of assistance in response to pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt, by Captain Brett E. Crozier (text) |url=https://www.voltairenet.org/article209667.html |website=Voltaire Network |language=en |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The letter provided his superiors with options, but recommended most<!--90%--> of the crew's evacuation, keeping only enough crew on board to maintain the nuclear reactor, provide security, and to [[Disinfection|sanitize the ship]]. He sent copies of the email to \"20 or 30\" people, including members of his staff and others not in his chain of command, but not including Admiral Baker.<ref name = Cohn/><ref name = losses/> The letter was leaked to the ''San Francisco Chronicle'', which published it the next day.<ref name = Gafni/>\n\n==Relieving Crozier of command and aftermath==\nOn 2 April, acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]] relieved Crozier of his command for sending the request for assistance over non-secure email to a \"broad array of people\" rather than up the chain of command, adding that Crozier \"allowed the complexity of the challenge of the COVID breakout on the ship to overwhelm his ability to act professionally\". Crozier will remain in the Navy and retain his rank.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> As Crozier disembarked, sailors were seen chanting \"Cap-tain Cro-zier\" in a video posted to [[Twitter]] captioned \"Wrongfully relieved of command but did right by the sailors.\"<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[NBC News]] |title=Videos show sailors cheering Navy captain relieved of command after raising alarm on coronavirus |date=3 April 2020 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/videos-show-sailors-cheering-navy-captain-relieved-command-after-raising-n1175946 |first=Janelle |last=Griffith}}</ref>\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?470922-1/us-navy-fires-captain-raised-alarm-coronavirus-aircraft-carrier U.S. Department of Defense briefing with Navy Secretary Modly in which he announces the relief of Capt. Crozier from his duty as the captain of the ''Theodore Roosevelt'', April 2, 2020], [[C-SPAN]]}}\nReaction to Crozier's dismissal was mixed. A ''Wall Street Journal'' story reported that on \"Capitol Hill and inside the Pentagon, lawmakers and officials reacted with confusion and anger over the dismissal\" of Crozier.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/captain-fired-by-navy-gets-rousing-farewell-from-sailors-11585933116?mod=hp_lista_pos2 |title=Captain Fired by Navy Gets Rousing Farewell from Sailors |last=Youssef |first=Nancy A. |last2=Lubold |first2=Gordon |date=3 April 2020 |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> A joint statement from four Democrats on the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|House Armed Services Committee]], including the committee chair, [[Adam Smith (politician)|Representative Adam Smith (D-WA)]], criticized Crozier's conduct, saying that \"Captain Crozier was justifiably concerned about the health and safety of his crew, but he did not handle the immense pressure appropriately. However, relieving him of his command is an overreaction.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Welna |first1=David |title=After Outcry Over Navy Captain Relieved Of Command, Assurances He Won't Be Expelled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/03/826920834/after-outcry-over-navy-captain-relieved-of-command-assurances-he-wont-be-expelle |website=npr.org |publisher=National Public Radio, Inc.}}</ref> [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] also criticized Crozier's letter on 4 April saying that it was \"not appropriate.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/04/trump-says-navy-captain-letter-asking-for-help-on-coronavirus-stricken-ship-was-terrible.html |title=Trump says Navy captain letter asking for help on coronavirus-stricken ship 'was terrible' |last=Feuer|first=William |date=4 April 2020|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nModly, U.S. Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]], and Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[Michael M. Gilday|Michael Gilday]] each defended the decision to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone>{{cite web |first=Rebecca |last=Kheel |title=Aircraft carrier captain removed from duty after pleading for help with coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/490892-aircraft-carrier-captain-to-be-removed-from-duty-after-pleading-for-help-with |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=2020-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Devan |last=Cole |title=Esper defends removing USS Theodore Roosevelt commander who sounded alarm over coronavirus |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/politics/mark-esper-uss-theodore-roosevelt-defends-removal-cnntv/index.html |work=CNN |date=2020-04-05 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Modly added that there was no White House pressure when the decision was made to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone />\n\nOn 6 April Modly traveled {{convert|8,000|mi}}<ref name=\"trip\"/> to Guam on a Navy executive jet; the trip was later reported to have cost taxpayers at least $243,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2020/04/08/trip-guam-center-top-navy-officials-resignation-cost-taxpayers-least-243000/?utm_campaign=wp_post_most&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&wpisrc=nl_most|title=Trip to Guam at center of top Navy official\u2019s resignation cost taxpayers over $243,000|last=Lamothe|first=Dan|date=April 8, 2020|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> He visited the ship in person and made a speech to the crew over the ship's [[public address system]]. He began by blaming the Chinese government for worsening the outbreak by not telling how bad the disease was. He continued by strongly criticizing Crozier, saying he was \"too na\u00efve or too stupid to be a commanding officer,\" if he did not realize that the letter would be leaked to the media.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ismay |first1=John |last2=Ziezulewicz |first2=Geoff |title=Acting Navy Secretary Slams Fired Captain as 'Stupid' |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/magazine/modly-crozier-coronavirus.html |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> Modly also scolded the ship's crew for cheering their captain as he left.<ref name=\"trip\"/>  The transcript and an audio recording of Modly's speech was subsequently leaked to the media.<ref name = Larison>{{cite news |last1=Larison |first1=Daniel |title=After Crozier Comments, Navy Secretary Modly Must Resign |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The American Conservative]] |url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/larison/modly-must-resign/ |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nModly's speech was widely criticized. [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Tim Kaine]] stated \"It's deeply disappointing that he would deliver a speech on board a U.S. aircraft carrier suggesting that Captain Crozier might be 'stupid'.\" [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] and [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Elaine Luria]] called for the removal of Modly, with Luria, a Navy veteran, saying he was \"in no way fit\" to lead the Navy.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Navy morale dives after firing of virus-riddled ship's captain |url=https://www.bignewsnetwork.com/news/264591472/us-navy-morale-dives-after-firing-of-virus-riddled-ship-captain |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Big News Network.com |language=en}}</ref> Chairperson of the [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Armed Services Committee's panel on military personnel]], [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Jackie Speier]] also criticized the trip.<ref name=\"ModlyCost\">{{cite news |last1=Brook |first1=Tom Vanden |title=Cost of Navy secretary's trip to Guam? $243,000, his job and isolation after coronavirus exposure |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/08/navy-secretary-trip-roosevelt-cost-243-000-leads-modly-ouster/2973486001/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Modly apologized for the comment.<ref name = Casiano/> The following day, he resigned his position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/acting-navy-secretary-resigns-in-wake-of-uss-roosevelt-11586287262 |title=Acting Navy Secretary Thomas Modly Resigns in Wake of USS Roosevelt Comments|last=Lubold|first=Gordon |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\nOn April 13, the first fatality among the sailors from the ship was announced.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-13/navy-sailor-from-uss-theodore-roosevelt-died-of-covid-19 \"Navy Sailor Dies in Guam After Virus Outbreak Aboard Carrier\"] Bloomberg.com</ref>\n\n==Number of confirmed cases==\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|colors=#F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y1= 3, 8, , , 33, , , , 93, , , , , 155, , 230, 286, 416, 447, 550, 585, 589<!--data missing-->\n|y1Title=Confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|colors=#88aaaaaa,#88436DF4,#88F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|xType=date\n|xAxisFormat=%_d %b\n|showSymbols=1\n|type=stackedarea\n|x= 2020/03/23, 2020/03/24, 2020/03/27, 2020/03/31, 2020/04/05, 2020/04/07, 2020/04/08, 2020/04/09, 2020/04/10, 2020/04/11, 2020/04/12, 2020/04/13\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y3= 3, 8, 33, 93, 155, 230, 286, 416, 447, 550, 585, 589<!--data missing-->\n|y2= ,,,593, 1500, 2037, 2588, 3170, 3284, 3673, 3724, 3922\n|y1= ,,,{{#expr:4865-593-93}},{{#expr:4865-1500-155}},{{#expr:4865-2037-230}},{{#expr:4865-2588-286}},{{#expr:4865-3170-416}},{{#expr:4865-3284-447}},{{#expr:4865-3673-550}},{{#expr:4865-3724-585}},{{#expr:4865-3922-589}}\n|y3Title=Confirmed cases\n|y2Title=Negative cases\n|y1Title=Untested\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic on naval ships]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania]]\n{{end div col}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Guam]]\n[[Category:2020 in military history]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by location|USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]]\n[[Category:Aircraft carriers involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Medicine in the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Water transport in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Guam]]\n[[Category:Disasters in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Health and transport]]\n[[Category:Health and military]]\n[[Category:Non-combat naval accidents]]\n[[Category:Military controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' (CVN-71)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic on board USS ''Theodore Roosevelt''\n| image           = CVN-71-2019-10-01-1.jpg\n| caption         = USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' in October 2019\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n| first_case      = {{ship|USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|2}}\n| arrival_date    = 24 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=24|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 1\n| confirmed_cases = 589<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenney |first1=Caitlin M. |title=Four more USS Theodore Roosevelt sailors hospitalized for the coronavirus|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/navy/four-more-uss-theodore-roosevelt-sailors-hospitalized-for-the-coronavirus-1.626022|accessdate=15 April 2020 |publisher= Stars and Stripes|date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARSCoV-2), the cause of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], was detected on the aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} in March 2020 while she was at sea. Affected crew members were evacuated and the ship was ordered to Guam. The captain, [[Brett Crozier]], wanted most of the crew to be removed from the ship to prevent the spread of the disease, but his superiors balked. After several days Crozier mailed multiple Navy officers begging for the ship to be largely evacuated because the virus could not be contained on board. The letter leaked to the press, and the next day the Navy ordered most of the crew to be taken ashore, but the captain was relieved of command by Acting Secretary of the Navy [[Thomas Modly]]. Modly's order was controversial and his later speech to the crew aboard the ''Roosevelt'', was critized. Modly resigned a few days later. By mid-April hundreds of crew members including Crozier had tested positive for the virus, and one had died.\n\n==Timeline==\nIn spring 2020, the [[United States Navy]] aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|2}} was on deployment in the Pacific.\n\n===March===\nOn 5 March, the ship made a four-day-long port call at [[Da Nang]], Vietnam. On the last night some sailors stayed at a hotel where two people had tested positive for [[COVID-19]], a coronavirus disease identified as the cause of an outbreak of respiratory illness. Upon learning this, the crew were ordered back to the ship and the sailors who had stayed at the hotel were isolated.<ref name = losses/> The ship departed on 9 March.<ref name=doTimeline>{{cite web |last1=Peniston |first1=Bradley |title=The Battle of USS Theodore Roosevelt: a Timeline |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/04/timeline-battle-uss-theodore-roosevelt/164408/ |website=Defense One |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200411135930/https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/04/timeline-battle-uss-theodore-roosevelt/164408/ |archivedate=11 April 2020 |date=13 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Over the next weeks the ship's medical team monitored the crew for any signs of infection.<ref name = losses/>\n\nOn 22 March, the first sailor tested positive.<ref name=doTimeline/> By 24 March, three sailors aboard had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/24/coronavirus-3-sailors-test-positive-military-readiness-affected/2910165001/ |title=Three sailors from USS Theodore Roosevelt have coronavirus, raising concerns about pandemic's strain on military |work=USA Today |last=Vanden Brook |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Vanden Brook|date=24 March 2020 |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWithin a few days, that number climbed to \"dozens.\" ''Theodore Roosevelt'' was ordered to [[Guam]] and docked on 27 March 2020.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 />\n\nOn 30 March, the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]], sent an [[Classified information in the United States#Unclassified|unclassified email]] to multiple Navy officials asking for help with the coronavirus epidemic on his ship. The email was sent to \"20 or 30\" Naval officers, including members of his staff and others not in his chain of command.<ref name = Cohn>{{Cite news |last=Cohn |first=Lindsay |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/05/this-is-what-was-so-unusual-about-us-navy-making-captain-brett-crozier-step-down/ |title=This is what was so unusual about the U.S. Navy making Captain Brett Crozier step down\u2014Members of the military can face multiple, sometimes competing, loyalties |access-date=6 April 2020 |work=The Washington Post |last2=Friend |first2=Alice |last3=Golby |first3=Jim}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, over 100 sailors tested positive.<ref name=Schogol>{{cite web |last1=Schogol |first1=Jeff |title=Navy captain says COVID-19 is spreading through his aircraft carrier so rapidly that most of the crew needs to get off |url=https://taskandpurpose.com/news/uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus-isolation |website=Task & Purpose |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406231152/https://taskandpurpose.com/news/uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus-isolation |archivedate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The letter was leaked to the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]],'' which published it.<ref name = Gafni>{{cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Exclusive-Captain-of-aircraft-carrier-with-15167883.php |title=Exclusive: Captain of aircraft carrier with growing coronavirus outbreak pleads for help from Navy|last1=Gafni|first1=Matthias |last2=Garofoli|first2=Joe |date=31 March 2020|work=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 1 April, the Navy ordered the aircraft carrier largely evacuated, with a skeleton crew to remain aboard the vessel to maintain the nuclear reactor, the fire-fighting equipment, the ship's galley, and a disinfection crew.<ref name= disinfectUssTRcvn71 >{{cite news|last=Peniston|first=Bradley |url=https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2020/03/us-navy-evacuating-aircraft-carrier-infected-coronavirus/164254/?oref=d-channelriver |title=US Navy Evacuating Aircraft Carrier Infected by Coronavirus|work=Defense One|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]] relieved Crozier of his command.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> According to Modly, Crozier didn't inform his [[Carrier Strike Group 9|superior on the ship]] about sending the letter, and Modly conferred with Crozier's [[chain of command]].<ref name=Gallagher>{{cite web |last1=Gallagher |first1=Sean |title=Aircraft carrier captain lost his command because of \u201cCatch-22\u201d COVID-19 dilemma |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/04/aircraft-carrier-captain-lost-his-command-because-of-catch-22-covid-19-dilemma/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407231021/https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/04/aircraft-carrier-captain-lost-his-command-because-of-catch-22-covid-19-dilemma/ |archivedate=7 April 2020 |language=en-us |date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, the Navy confirmed that 155 sailors had been infected and that 1,500 sailors had been removed from the ship, a lower number than the Navy had projected several days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/sailors-uss-teddy-roosevelt-positive-covid-19-navy |title=155 sailors on USS Theodore Roosevelt test positive for coronavirus, 42 percent of all Navy infections |work=Fox News |last=Ruiz |first=Michael |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Modly traveled to Guam to visit the ship in person.<ref name=\"trip\">{{cite news |title=Blistering Reprimand from Navy Secretary |date=7 April 2020 |author=Helene Cooper |work=[[The New York Times]] |page=A11}}</ref> He made a speech to the crew over the ship's [[public address system]], strongly criticizing Crozier. The transcript and an audio recording of Modly's speech were subsequently leaked to the media.<ref name = Larison/> Later that day, Modly apologized for the comment.<ref name = Casiano>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/acting-navy-secretary-uss-theodore-roosevelt-speech-calls-for-his-firing |title=Trump hints that he may get involved in Navy episode as Modly issues apology|last1=Casiano|first1=Louis |last2=Aaro|first2=David |date=7 April 2020|work=Fox News|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> He resigned from his post the following day.\n\nOn 7 April, the Navy said 61% of ''Theodore Roosevelt''{{'}}s crew had been tested for COVID-19 and 173 members had tested positive, including Captain Crozier. None were hospitalized. Two thousand sailors \u2014 just under half the total crew \u2014 had been moved ashore.<ref name=\"Guardian20200407\">{{cite news |last1=Borger|first1=Julian |last2=|first2=|title=US navy official apologises for calling captain behind coronavirus memo 'naive or stupid' |date=7 April 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/06/navy-coronavirus-ship-theodore-roosevelt-thomas-modly |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, the Navy reported that 416 crew members had tested positive for the virus, and that one quarantined sailor was hospitalized in intensive care after being found unconscious in his quarantine quarters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/uss-theodore-roosevelt-sailor-with-coronavirus-taken-to-icu-2020-4|title=A USS Theodore Roosevelt sailor with coronavirus was taken to the ICU as the number of cases on the aircraft carrier rises|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|date=April 9, 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, it was reported that more than 90% of the crew had been tested for the coronavirus, and 550 crew members had tested positive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/100-new-coronavirus-cases-uss-theodore-roosevelt-550-total-2020-4|title=100 more sailors from the USS Theodore Roosevelt have tested positive for coronavirus, making up 75% of the Navy's total cases worldwide|last=Holmes|first=Aaron|date=11 April 2020|work=Business Insider|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=McNamara |first1=Audrey |title=Coronavirus cases on USS Theodore Roosevelt spike to 550|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-cases-on-uss-theodore-roosevelt-spike-to-550-2020-04-11/|accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=CBS |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 12 April, 585 crew members had tested positive. <ref name = dies/>\n\nOn 13 April, the hospitalized sailor died.<ref name = dies>politico.com: [https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/13/sailor-uss-roosevelt-dies-coronavirus-183164 ''Sailor from USS Theodore Roosevelt dies of coronavirus'']</ref>\n\n==Crozier's letter==\n[[File:Brett E. Crozier (2).jpg|thumb|Ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]]]]\nWhen the ship arrived in Guam on 26 March the ship's commanding officer, Captain [[Brett Crozier]], wanted to have most of the crew immediately taken ashore, saying it was impossible to prevent the spread of the virus in the close quarters of the ship. Rear Adm. [[Stuart P. Baker]], who was the commanding officer of [[Carrier Strike Group 9]] and thus Crozier's immediate superior, disagreed, feeling such an action was impractical and too drastic.<ref name = losses>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/coronavirus-roosevelt-carrier-crozier.html?campaign_id=60&emc=edit_na_20200413&instance_id=0&nl=breaking-news&ref=cta&regi_id=16153474&segment_id=24971&user_id=e9848bda5d7546386411f6e2fbdaf95e|title=\u2018There Will Be Losses\u2019: How a Captain\u2019s Plea Exposed a Rift in the Military|date=13 April 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Crozier sent an email to communicate the status of his ship and its crew, saying it was not possible to observe [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]]/Navy<ref>{{cite web |title=Restriction of Movement (ROM) guidance. Navy mitigation measures in response to Novel Coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.public.navy.mil/bupers-npc/reference/messages/Documents/NAVADMINS/NAV2020/NAV20083.txt |publisher=NAVADMIN |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> recommendations for individual quarantine or [[social distancing]] aboard the carrier. Crozier referred to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on Diamond Princess|viral spread on the less crowded cruise ship ''Diamond Princess'']] as an example of [[Basic reproduction number|how quickly a virus can spread]] on a crowded vessel.<ref name = Gafni/><ref name=\"documentcloud\">{{cite web|url=https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/6821571/TR-COVID-19-Assistance-Request.pdf |date=29 March 2020|title=Request for assistance in response to COVID-19 pandemic |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Voltaire>{{cite web |title=Request of assistance in response to pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt, by Captain Brett E. Crozier (text) |url=https://www.voltairenet.org/article209667.html |website=Voltaire Network |language=en |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The letter provided his superiors with options, but recommended most<!--90%--> of the crew's evacuation, keeping only enough crew on board to maintain the nuclear reactor, provide security, and to [[Disinfection|sanitize the ship]]. He sent copies of the email to \"20 or 30\" people, including members of his staff and others not in his chain of command, but not including Admiral Baker.<ref name = Cohn/><ref name = losses/> The letter was leaked to the ''San Francisco Chronicle'', which published it the next day.<ref name = Gafni/>\n\n==Relieving Crozier of command and aftermath==\nOn 2 April, acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]] relieved Crozier of his command for sending the request for assistance over non-secure email to a \"broad array of people\" rather than up the chain of command, adding that Crozier \"allowed the complexity of the challenge of the COVID breakout on the ship to overwhelm his ability to act professionally\". Crozier will remain in the Navy and retain his rank.<ref name=\"NBC Crozier Relieved\">{{cite news |last1=Kube |first1=Courtney |last2=Gains |first2=Mosheh |title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> As Crozier disembarked, sailors were seen chanting \"Cap-tain Cro-zier\" in a video posted to [[Twitter]] captioned \"Wrongfully relieved of command but did right by the sailors.\"<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[NBC News]] |title=Videos show sailors cheering Navy captain relieved of command after raising alarm on coronavirus |date=3 April 2020 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/videos-show-sailors-cheering-navy-captain-relieved-command-after-raising-n1175946 |first=Janelle |last=Griffith}}</ref>\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?470922-1/us-navy-fires-captain-raised-alarm-coronavirus-aircraft-carrier U.S. Department of Defense briefing with Navy Secretary Modly in which he announces the relief of Capt. Crozier from his duty as the captain of the ''Theodore Roosevelt'', April 2, 2020], [[C-SPAN]]}}\nReaction to Crozier's dismissal was mixed. A ''Wall Street Journal'' story reported that on \"Capitol Hill and inside the Pentagon, lawmakers and officials reacted with confusion and anger over the dismissal\" of Crozier.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/captain-fired-by-navy-gets-rousing-farewell-from-sailors-11585933116?mod=hp_lista_pos2 |title=Captain Fired by Navy Gets Rousing Farewell from Sailors |last=Youssef |first=Nancy A. |last2=Lubold |first2=Gordon |date=3 April 2020 |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> A joint statement from four Democrats on the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|House Armed Services Committee]], including the committee chair, [[Adam Smith (politician)|Representative Adam Smith (D-WA)]], criticized Crozier's conduct, saying that \"Captain Crozier was justifiably concerned about the health and safety of his crew, but he did not handle the immense pressure appropriately. However, relieving him of his command is an overreaction.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Welna |first1=David |title=After Outcry Over Navy Captain Relieved Of Command, Assurances He Won't Be Expelled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/03/826920834/after-outcry-over-navy-captain-relieved-of-command-assurances-he-wont-be-expelle |website=npr.org |publisher=National Public Radio, Inc.}}</ref> [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] also criticized Crozier's letter on 4 April saying that it was \"not appropriate.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/04/trump-says-navy-captain-letter-asking-for-help-on-coronavirus-stricken-ship-was-terrible.html |title=Trump says Navy captain letter asking for help on coronavirus-stricken ship 'was terrible' |last=Feuer|first=William |date=4 April 2020|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nModly, U.S. Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]], and Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[Michael M. Gilday|Michael Gilday]] each defended the decision to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone>{{cite web |first=Rebecca |last=Kheel |title=Aircraft carrier captain removed from duty after pleading for help with coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/490892-aircraft-carrier-captain-to-be-removed-from-duty-after-pleading-for-help-with |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=2020-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Devan |last=Cole |title=Esper defends removing USS Theodore Roosevelt commander who sounded alarm over coronavirus |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/politics/mark-esper-uss-theodore-roosevelt-defends-removal-cnntv/index.html |work=CNN |date=2020-04-05 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Modly added that there was no White House pressure when the decision was made to remove Crozier.<ref name=croziergone />\n\nOn 6 April Modly traveled {{convert|8,000|mi}}<ref name=\"trip\"/> to Guam on a Navy executive jet; the trip was later reported to have cost taxpayers at least $243,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2020/04/08/trip-guam-center-top-navy-officials-resignation-cost-taxpayers-least-243000/?utm_campaign=wp_post_most&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&wpisrc=nl_most|title=Trip to Guam at center of top Navy official\u2019s resignation cost taxpayers over $243,000|last=Lamothe|first=Dan|date=April 8, 2020|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> He visited the ship in person and made a speech to the crew over the ship's [[public address system]]. He began by blaming the Chinese government for worsening the outbreak by not telling how bad the disease was. He continued by strongly criticizing Crozier, saying he was \"too na\u00efve or too stupid to be a commanding officer,\" if he did not realize that the letter would be leaked to the media.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ismay |first1=John |last2=Ziezulewicz |first2=Geoff |title=Acting Navy Secretary Slams Fired Captain as 'Stupid' |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/magazine/modly-crozier-coronavirus.html |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> Modly also scolded the ship's crew for cheering their captain as he left.<ref name=\"trip\"/>  The transcript and an audio recording of Modly's speech was subsequently leaked to the media.<ref name = Larison>{{cite news |last1=Larison |first1=Daniel |title=After Crozier Comments, Navy Secretary Modly Must Resign |date=6 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The American Conservative]] |url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/larison/modly-must-resign/ |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nModly's speech was widely criticized. [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Tim Kaine]] stated \"It's deeply disappointing that he would deliver a speech on board a U.S. aircraft carrier suggesting that Captain Crozier might be 'stupid'.\" [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] and [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Elaine Luria]] called for the removal of Modly, with Luria, a Navy veteran, saying he was \"in no way fit\" to lead the Navy.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Navy morale dives after firing of virus-riddled ship's captain |url=https://www.bignewsnetwork.com/news/264591472/us-navy-morale-dives-after-firing-of-virus-riddled-ship-captain |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Big News Network.com |language=en}}</ref> Chairperson of the [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Armed Services Committee's panel on military personnel]], [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Jackie Speier]] also criticized the trip.<ref name=\"ModlyCost\">{{cite news |last1=Brook |first1=Tom Vanden |title=Cost of Navy secretary's trip to Guam? $243,000, his job and isolation after coronavirus exposure |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/08/navy-secretary-trip-roosevelt-cost-243-000-leads-modly-ouster/2973486001/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Modly apologized for the comment.<ref name = Casiano/> The following day, he resigned his position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/acting-navy-secretary-resigns-in-wake-of-uss-roosevelt-11586287262 |title=Acting Navy Secretary Thomas Modly Resigns in Wake of USS Roosevelt Comments|last=Lubold|first=Gordon |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\nOn April 13, the first fatality among the sailors from the ship was announced.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-13/navy-sailor-from-uss-theodore-roosevelt-died-of-covid-19 \"Navy Sailor Dies in Guam After Virus Outbreak Aboard Carrier\"] Bloomberg.com</ref>\n\n==Number of confirmed cases==\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|colors=#F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y1= 3, 8, , , 33, , , , 93, , , , , 155, , 230, 286, 416, 447, 550, 585, 589<!--data missing-->\n|y1Title=Confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|colors=#88aaaaaa,#88436DF4,#88F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|xType=date\n|xAxisFormat=%_d %b\n|showSymbols=1\n|type=stackedarea\n|x= 2020/03/23, 2020/03/24, 2020/03/27, 2020/03/31, 2020/04/05, 2020/04/07, 2020/04/08, 2020/04/09, 2020/04/10, 2020/04/11, 2020/04/12, 2020/04/13\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y3= 3, 8, 33, 93, 155, 230, 286, 416, 447, 550, 585, 589<!--data missing-->\n|y2= ,,,593, 1500, 2037, 2588, 3170, 3284, 3673, 3724, 3922\n|y1= ,,,{{#expr:4865-593-93}},{{#expr:4865-1500-155}},{{#expr:4865-2037-230}},{{#expr:4865-2588-286}},{{#expr:4865-3170-416}},{{#expr:4865-3284-447}},{{#expr:4865-3673-550}},{{#expr:4865-3724-585}},{{#expr:4865-3922-589}}\n|y3Title=Confirmed cases\n|y2Title=Negative cases\n|y1Title=Untested\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic on naval ships]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania]]\n{{end div col}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Guam]]\n[[Category:2020 in military history]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by location|USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]]\n[[Category:Aircraft carriers involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Medicine in the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Water transport in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Guam]]\n[[Category:Disasters in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Health and transport]]\n[[Category:Health and military]]\n[[Category:Non-combat naval accidents]]\n[[Category:Military controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Algernon (psychiatrick\u00fd experiment)", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_on_USS_Theodore_Roosevelt_(CVN-71)"}
{"title_page": "Fred Page Cup", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{about|the Eastern Canadian Junior \"A\" ice hockey championship|the BCHL championship trophy|British Columbia Hockey League}}\n{{Infobox sports award\n| name        = Fred Page Cup\n| image_size  = 250px\n| image       = Fred Page Cup Logo.png\n| caption     = \n| sport       = Ice hockey\n| givenfor    = Eastern region champion\n| league      = [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]]\n| country     = Canada\n| first       = 1995\n| mostwins    = [[Carleton Place Canadians]] (3)\n| mostrecent  = [[Ottawa Jr. Senators]] (2019) (2nd title)\n}}\n\nThe '''Fred Page Cup''' is a championship [[ice hockey]] trophy, won by a tournament conducted by the [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]].  The award is given to the winner of a [[Round-robin tournament|round-robin]] and playoff between the Bogart Cup champions of the [[Central Canada Hockey League]], the Kent Cup champions of the [[Maritime Junior Hockey League]], La Coupe NAPA Champions of the [[Quebec Junior Hockey League]], and a pre-determined host team.  The winner of the Fred Page Cup moves on to the [[Centennial Cup]], the national Junior A championship.  The trophy was donated by the then-called [[Quebec Provincial Junior Hockey League]] in 1994\u201395.\n\n==History==\nThe first Fred Page Cup was awarded in 1995.  The trophy was donated by the [[Quebec Junior Hockey League|Quebec Provincial Junior A Hockey League]] to create an Eastern Canadian Championship in honour of past [[Hockey Canada|Canadian Amateur Hockey Association]] President [[Fred Page]].  The 1995 Championship marked the first time teams outside of the [[maritime provinces]] were allowed to compete for the Eastern Canadian Championship for a berth to the [[Royal Bank Cup|National Championship]].  Now allowed are the maritime champions, the Quebec champions, and the [[Ottawa]] District champions of the [[Central Canada Hockey League]].  Prior to 1995, the Callaghan Cup was the championship trophy of Eastern Canada to be played for by a representative of the maritime provinces.  Early championships were dominated by the [[Island Junior Hockey League (1973\u20131991)|Island Junior Hockey League]].  In the early 1990s, the top teams of the IJHL jumped to the [[Maritime Junior A Hockey League]].\n\nThe Ottawa Jr. Senators were awarded the 2003 Fred Page Cup in the fall of 2001, but over the summer of 2002, the tournament was awarded the Cornwall Colts instead. This was mostly due to the size of the Jr. Senators arena and the conflict with other groups, therefore the event couldn't be attainable. The [[Nepean Raiders]] surprisingly never bid for the tournament, despite reaching the league finals eight times between 2003 and 2013. The event could not be supported with a low fan-base and reaching an agreement with the city. The 2006 Fred Page Cup was then awarded to [[Pembroke, Ontario]] and the [[Pembroke Lumber Kings]].\n\nTo date,{{when|date=March 2020}} the [[Central Canada Hockey League]] has won the Fred Page Cup seven times, winning the Royal Bank Cup finals once, ([[Pembroke Lumber Kings]]) since its inception in 1996. The [[Quebec Junior Hockey League]] has won the Fred Page Cup only three times, and no team from Quebec have qualified for the Royal Bank Cup finals. The [[Maritime Junior A Hockey League]] is the only league to win the Fred Page Cup and have teams win the Royal Bank Cup, as the [[Summerside Capitals]] won in 1997 and the [[Halifax Oland Exports]] won in 2002.\n\nThe 2010 Fred Page Cup was awarded to the [[Brockville Braves]], who also hosted the tournament in 1997. Brockville won the 2010 Fred Page Cup by defeating the Pembroke Lumber Kings 5\u20131. The Braves are the second host team since the 1998\u201399 [[Charlottetown Abbies]], who defeated the CCHL's Hawkesbury Hawks 2\u20130 at the [[Charlottetown Civic Centre]]. The [[Pembroke Lumber Kings]] are the only team to compete in six consecutive Fred Page Cup tournaments from 2006 to 2011, winning the tournament twice in 2007 and 2011, and losing the finals in 2006 and 2008.\n\nIn 2009, the traditional circulation was broken, when [[Dieppe, New Brunswick]], and the Dieppe Commandos were awarded the tournament instead of a team from the [[Central Canada Hockey League]]. Maritime Hockey League champions [[Summerside Western Capitals]] elected to play their Fred Page Cup games in [[Summerside, Prince Edward Island]], but this idea was quickly nixed because of a disagreement from the Quebec Junior Hockey League champion [[Sherbrooke Cougars]].\n\nThe Kanata Stallions were chosen to host the 2012 Fred Page Cup, despite the team's poor performances since re-branding from the Kanata Valley Lasers in 2002. The Stallions managed to qualify for the semi-finals and avoided elimination with an over-time win over their crosstown rivals Nepean Raiders. The Kanata Stallions finished in third place in the tournament.\n\nThe [[Carleton Place Canadians]] became the first team to win back-to-back Fred Page Cup championships during the tournament's inception in 1996. They continued their streak with three straight wins from 2014 to 2016.\n\nThe 2018 tournament was awarded to Ottawa, which made it the second time the tournament was played in the Ottawa area. Pembroke placed a bid, but was passed over in favor of Ottawa. Smiths Falls placed a bid, but withdrew.\n\n==Champions==\n{| cellpadding=\"0\" \n|- align=\"left\" style=\"vertical-align: top\" \n| \n| \n{| cellpadding=\"1\" style=\"font-size: 90%; border: 1px solid gray;\" \n|- align=\"center\" style=\"font-size: larger;\" \n| colspan=5 | '''Fred Page Cup Eastern Canada Junior A Champions''' \n|- style=\"background:lightblue;\" \n| '''Year''' || '''Champions''' || '''Runners-Up''' || '''Host Team''' ||'''City'''|| \n|- bgcolor=\n|1995\t\n|'''[[Joliette Nationals]]''' ([[QJAAAHL|QPJHL]])\t\t\n|[[Cornwall Colts]] ([[Central Canada Hockey League|CJHL]])\t\t\n| [[Joliette Nationals]] ([[QJAAAHL|QPJHL]])\t\